Deputy President William Ruto's shoot -to &ndash;kill order to flash out armed Pokot bandits in Baringo county is welcome, professionals from the Tugen community have said.Led by Kenya Union of Post Primary Education Teachers secretary Sammy Chelanga, they said this will help restore peace.&ldquo;Bandits are not people to be played around with. It is either you kill them or they will kill tyou,&rdquo; he said.Chelanga told off NASA leaders, who said on Saturday in Eldoret that Ruto cannot give shoot to kill orders.He said the leaders are not as affected as the Baringo people.Raila Odinga (ODM), Kalonzo Musyoka (Wiper), Musalia Mudavadi (ANC)and Moses Wetang'ula (Ford Kenya) addressed a rally at 64 Stadium in Eldoret town on Saturday.&ldquo;The shoot to kill order is a clear indication the government of the day is unable to manage banditry with diplomacy and in a dignified way,&rdquo; Kalonzo said .Chelanga, who is aspiring to be Baringo North MP on the Maendeleo Chap Chap ticket, said many lives have been lost, properties stolen and people rendered homeless by the armed pokot bandits. He said it is time the government provides an urgent solution.He was accompanied by German-based Business man Joshua Kandie( Parliamentary aspirant Baringo Central) and Kisii University-Kabarnet town campus Director Joseph Kandie.